provider "aws" {
  region = "us-west-2"  # Specify your AWS region
}

# Define the number of instances we want to create
variable "instance_count" {
  default = 3  # We will create 3 EC2 instances
}

# Create multiple EC2 instances using count
resource "aws_instance" "example" {
  count = var.instance_count  # The number of instances to create

  ami           = "ami-0c55b159cbfafe1f0"  # Example AMI ID (Amazon Linux 2)
  instance_type = "t2.micro"

  tags = {
    Name = "ExampleInstance-${count.index}"  # Use count.index to create unique names
  }
}

# Output the instance IDs
output "instance_ids" {
  value = aws_instance.example[*].id
}


In Terraform, the count parameter is used to manage the creation of multiple identical resources. This can be helpful when you need to create
several instances of a resource based on a condition or a given number.
 
provider "aws"{
region= "ap-south-1"
}

variable "instance_count"{
default=10
}

resource "aws_instance" "prerna"{
name="prerna"
ami="ami0006668992678"
instance_type=t2.micro
count=var.instance_count
tags = {
    Name = "ExampleInstance-${count.index}"  # Use count.index to create unique names
  }}

output "instance"{
value="aws_instance.prerna.count[*].id"
}


The terraform taint command marks a resource as "tainted," meaning Terraform will destroy and recreate the resource on the next terraform apply.

terraform destroy -target=aws_instance.example

